      "content": "The assertion that originalism is the \"most logically consistent\" framework is an acknowledgment of its structural coherence. The living constitution approach, conversely, is a philosophical justification for judicial policymaking, allowing judges to legislate from the bench based on present-day moral concerns. While originalism seeks to be a form of legal science by anchoring interpretation in history, the living constitution is fundamentally an exercise in judicial discretion, which is why critics label it as activism.",
      "source": "target",
